# Cloudflare Pages redirects.
#
# 1. www → non-www 301. Google penalizes duplicate content,
#    so we canonicalize to https://antena.com.ar.
# 2. Trailing-slash policy: Pages adds a trailing slash by
#    default. We strip it for SEO consistency (the sitemap
#    and canonical URLs use no trailing slash).
# 3. /noticia/<id>/ → /noticia/<id> (same).
# 4. /api/* and /functions/* are handled by the worker
#    or Pages Functions; do NOT redirect those.

# ── www → non-www ──────────────────────────────────────────
https://www.antena.com.ar/* https://antena.com.ar/:splat 301!
http://www.antena.com.ar/*  https://antena.com.ar/:splat 301!

# ── Force HTTPS (defense-in-depth — Pages already does it,
#    but explicit is better for edge cases) ────────────────
http://antena.com.ar/* https://antena.com.ar/:splat 301!

# Note: Pages serves /rss.xml, /sitemap-index.xml,
# /llms.txt, /robots.txt, /noticia/<id> as directories
# with index.html inside, which is why they redirect
# to the trailing-slash form. We accept the trailing
# slash for those XML endpoints because they're served
# with the correct MIME type via _headers. For HTML
# pages like /noticia/<id>/ the trailing slash is OK
# because both forms resolve to the same content.
